The aim of this analysis

Today I will assume the role of a data analyst working for a wholesale distributor. My objective is to analyze the customer spending data and use clustering techniques to identify unique customer segments. Some of the questions we aim to answer include the following:

  • Can we group customers into meaningful segments based on their purchasing behavior?
  • What characteristics define each customer segment?
  • How can the business use these insights to improve making decisions, marketing strategies, and customer service?

About the data

The link to the dataset: Wholesale Customers Dataset

The Wholesale Customers Dataset was found on Kaggle.com. The dataset contains information about the annual spending habits of clients of a wholesale distributor. The dataset is useful for unsupervised learning techniques like clustering because it does not have predefined labels and provides clear behavioral features. The features included in the dataset are:

  • Channel: The type of customer
  • Region: The geographic region
  • Fresh: The annual spending on fresh products
  • Milk: The annual spending on milk products
  • Grocery: The annual spending on grocery items
  • Frozen: The annual spending on frozen products
  • Detergents_Paper: The annual spending on detergents and paper products
  • Delicassen: The annual spending on delicatessen items, which are gourmet foods

The dataset contains 440 records (customers) and 8 features.

Why this dataset? Because it is ideal for clustering! The labels are not predefined, the dataset contains natural groupings based on customer purchasing behavior, and exploration is possible of how spending patterns can indicate different customer profiles

What is clustering?

Clustering is an unsupervised machine learning technique used to group similar data points together based on similar patterns or characteristics found in the data. Compared to supervised learning, where the goal is to predicted labeled outcomes, clustering has no predefined labels. Instead, it identifies natural groupings or structures within the data.

In this project, clustering allows us to segment the wholesale customers based on their purchasing behaviors, even if we do not have predefined categories for them.

What is K-Means Clustering? It is a popular and straightforward clustering algorithm. This is how it works:

  1. Choose the number of clusters (k)
  2. Initialize the k centroids randomly
  3. From k clusters by assigning each data point to the nearest centroid
  4. Calculate the new centroids by taking the mean of all data points in each cluster
  5. Repeat step 3 and 4 until the centroids stabilize

The goal is to minimize how close the points in a cluster are to each other and to maximize how distinct the clusters are from one another.

Data Understanding/Visualization

Before creating a cluster model, it is important to actually understand the structure of the data and identify any trends, patterns, or even anomalies. This step of the process helps in ensuring that the clustering model is built on data that is understood, and it guides decisions around the preprocessing step and feature selection.

Preprocessing

Before we create the clustering model, we have to dive into preprocessing! we have to especially because clustering is highly sensitive to how the data is scaled and shaped.

In[50]:
# Dropping categorical features
# Since we are focused on spending behavior, we will drop Channel and Region for clustering

X = df.drop(['Channel', 'Region'], axis=1)

We are clustering based on numerical spending patterns alone, so we don't really need the categorical features even if they are encoded.

In[51]:
# Log transformations
# the data is heavily skewed, meaning a few customers spend a lot more than others
# This compresses the scale and reduces the effect of extreme outliers, making the clusters more balanced

X_log = np.log1p(X)
In[52]:
# Scaling the features (Standardization)

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_log)

Features with larger scales would dominate the clusters. Scaling them will ensure all features contribute equally to distance computations!

Clustering

Now, it is time to use the clustering models to predict purchasing behavior. We will use K-Means and Agglomerative Clustering today, and compare them to see which one works better.

K-Means
In[56]:
# We will try different values for k to find the optimal number

inertia = []
K =range(1, 11)
for k in K:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(X_scaled)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# Plotting the elbow method
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
plt.plot(K, inertia, 'bo-')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.title('Elbow Method For Optimal k')
plt.show()

The elbow appears at k = 3, which is the point in the curve where the inertia starts to flatten out.

In[54]:
# Fitting the model
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=42)
kmeans.fit(X_scaled)
labels_kmeans = kmeans.labels_

Why K-Means? I used K-Means because it is simple and fast to use, and it works well when clusters are spherical and balanced. It helps reveal natural customer groups based on similar spending habits, and it also works well after scaling.

Pros?

  • It is easy to implement and interpret
  • Scalable to large datasets
  • Efficient when it comes to time complexity

Cons?

  • It is sensitive to outliers and initial centroid placement
  • It is required to predefine the number of clusters (k)
  • It doesn't handle nonspherical clusters well
Agglomerative Clustering
In[57]:
# Fitting the model

agg = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=3)
labels_agg = agg.fit_predict(X_scaled)

Why use Agglomerative Clustering? It doesn't require k to be defined upfront when visualized with a dendrogram. It captures more organic and less symmetrical cluster shapes. Finally, it is good for smaller datasets like this one.

Pros?

  • It doesn't assume the shape or size of the clusters
  • We can choose k by visualizing with a dendrogram
  • It is more robust to noise and outliers in some cases

Cons?

  • It is not scalable to very large datasets and is very computationally expensive
  • a cluster cannot be split once it is merged

Clustering Analysis

We arrived at 3 clusters after using K-Means and Agglomerative, Let us analyze our clusters now!

Cluster 0: High spending on Grocery, Milk, and Detergents_paper. Low spending on Fresh, Frozen, and Delicassen. The customers seem to prioritize shelf stable or processed goods, which align with retail shops, convenience stores, or small stores, where the volume of product or shelf life matter more than freshness.

Cluster 1: High spending on Fresh, moderate spending on Frozen, and Low spending on everything else. This cluster is focused on fresh goods and some frozen foods, which is typical of restaurants, hotels, or catering services, where freshness is key and there is less emphasis in grocery or paper products.

Cluster 2: High spending on Fresh, Milk, and Grocery, and decent spending on everything else. Those are likely high volume buyers like large hotels or wholesale food services. They buy everything in bulk indicating larger scale operations with different needs.

We could tailor marketing strategies and make inventory decisions based on these clusters! Understanding these segments could help businesses optimize product offerings and even predict future buying behavior.

Impact of this project

Positive Impacts
  1. Improving business efficiency: businesses can tailor marketing strategies, manage inventory more effectively, and streamline supply chains, reducing waste and improving profit margins.
  2. Personalizing th customer experience: Clustering allows suppliers to understand different customer needs and behaviors.
  3. Data driven decision making: Companies can rely on empirical evidence to inform their operations instead of assumptions
Negative Impacts
  1. Missing the data and privacy issues: Improper use of clustering insights might lead to intrusive profiling or discrimination.
  2. Bias: outliers or niche customers might be ignored.
  3. Questionable ethical decisions: There is a risk that high value customers like cluster 2 are prioritized unfairly. This can reinforce inequality!
